on office location is printed as 'काठमाडौं' in block /page/0/SectionHeader/1. This matches the extracted value.\n\nPASS:\nConclusion: काठमाडौं, which agrees with the extraction.", 'verification_status': 'PASS'}], 'notes': 'All fields have been verified against the single page document. The extraction is highly accurate and matches the document text exactly.', 'prompt': 'You are verifying field values in extracted data, working through one chunk of the document at a time. You see the schema, the extracted data, and the running verification state from prior chunks.\n\nPer-chunk header: this is chunk 1 of 1. THIS IS THE LAST CHUNK.\n\nBefore you finalize updates on this chunk, scan the rolling verification state for any field still at PENDING. For each such field, emit an update moving it out of PENDING:\n  - PASS if the extracted value looks correct given everything you\'ve seen     across all chunks.\n  - FAIL_FIX if you have a specific concern with feedback to act on.\n  - FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE if the document doesn\'t support a correct value AND no     fix is achievable from this document.\n  - ITEMS_MISSING (lists only) if the list is missing entries.\nDo not leave any field at PENDING after this final chunk. PENDING is only acceptable as an intermediate state during the walk.\n\nFor each field you produce a complete `FieldStatus` update. Do not emit updates for fields you have no bearing on this chunk; their prior state will carry forward.\n\n==== verification_status ====\n\n`verification_status` is a single signal that covers BOTH value-correctness and citation-correctness for the field. Use the value\'s correctness as the primary axis; if (and only if) the value itself passes, judge its citations.\n\nFor scalar fields (any non-list path):\n  PENDING        — no chunk has affirmed or contradicted the value yet.\n  PASS           — the value is correct AND the citations contain                    sufficient and correct evidence for it. Extra                    citations are fine; the criterion is that the cited                    blocks back the value.\n  FAIL_CITATIONS — the value is correct, but the citations are wrong or                    insufficient (a cited block is incorrect, OR the                    citations don\'t cover the minimum sufficient evidence                    for the value). Synthesis should KEEP the value and                    only update the citations. Feedback must say which                    block IDs would be the correct minimum sufficient                    evidence.\n  FAIL_FIX       — the value is wrong, but the document supports a                    correct value. Feedback must say what the correct                    value is and which block IDs back it.\n  FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE — the document doesn\'t support any value here, OR                    the document is genuinely contradictory across chunks                    with no winner.\n\nCitations principle (applies to PASS / FAIL_CITATIONS): citations on a scalar wrapper should be the MINIMUM SUFFICIENT EVIDENCE for the value. Extra citations are acceptable; insufficient or incorrect citations are not. If a wrong value happens to have technically-sufficient citations to a wrong block, that\'s still FAIL_FIX — value-correctness comes first.\n\nFor list fields (paths whose value in the data is an array):\n  PENDING       — no chunk has affirmed completeness or surfaced missing                   items yet.\n  PASS          — the list is COMPLETE: every entry the document contains                   for this list is present in the extraction. Before                   setting PASS, compare the item count stated in the                   verification state feedback (e.g. "The extraction                   contains 9 items in this list") against the number of                   items visible in the document. If the document contains                   more items than the extraction, the status is                   ITEMS_MISSING, not PASS — even if the items that are                   present are individually correct.\n  ITEMS_MISSING — the document contains entries that are not present in                   the extraction. Feedback must describe: how many items                   the document contains vs how many the extraction has,                   and which specific items are missing (with block IDs                   where they appear) so that the next iteration can find                   and include them. Use this ONLY when the document                   actually contains entries the extraction omitted — never                   for a list the document does not address (see                   FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE below).\n  FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE — the same verdict defined above, applied to a list:                   the document supports no value here because it contains                   no items for this field at all (the correct value is an                   empty list or null). An absent list is FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE,                   NOT ITEMS_MISSING — ITEMS_MISSING is only for a list the                   document DOES populate but the extraction under-captured.\n\nImportant: the verification state for each list path includes the actual item count from the extraction (e.g. "The extraction contains 9 items in this list"). Use this count as the ground truth for how many items the extraction has — do NOT attempt to count array elements in the extracted JSON yourself. Compare this count against the document.\n\n==== How to choose the status on each update ====\n\nFor every update you emit, follow these three steps in order.\n\nStep 1 — Decide what the document actually says for this field, using this chunk\'s evidence plus the rolling state. This is YOUR conclusion.\n\nStep 2 — Compare your conclusion to synth\'s value, and pick the status from this table:\n\n    Your conclusion                                      Status\n    -------------------------------------------------    --------------------\n    Same value as synth, citations OK                    PASS\n    Same value as synth, citations wrong/insufficient    FAIL_CITATIONS\n    Different value (document supports X)                FAIL_FIX\n                                                         (write X in feedback)\n    Document supports no value here                      FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE\n\nStep 3 — Your status describes YOUR conclusion in this chunk. It does not anchor to whatever a prior chunk wrote. If a prior chunk emitted FAIL_FIX but your evidence now shows synth was right, emit PASS — do NOT keep FAIL_FIX just because the prior chunk used it.\n\nStep 4 — Status and feedback must always agree. They describe the same conclusion.\n\n==== Locked fields ====\n\nSome entries in the verification state may already be at status PASS or FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE. Those verdicts came from a prior iteration of the loop and are LOCKED — they are considered final across iterations. DO NOT emit updates for any locked field, even if a fresh look at the chunk makes you think you\'d judge it differently. The goal is stability: once a verdict has stuck, it shouldn\'t flip just because the model is re-evaluating. If you spot what looks like a regression on a locked field (e.g. the value visibly changed between iterations and now seems wrong), note it in your `notes` field for downstream human review — but do not produce a status change.\n\n==== Field type and text fidelity ====\n\nEvery field declares a `value` type in the schema (string, number, integer, boolean) and may carry constraints (`enum`, `format`, `pattern`) and a description. Judge the value against ALL of these — the type, the constraints, AND the description. The description takes precedence: when it specifies a particular form, the value must follow the description, not the document\'s raw text.\n\nSTRING fields: the default is verbatim — the value must match the document text exactly (same wording, punctuation including trailing periods, capitalization, prefixes and qualifiers), and a value that paraphrases, abbreviates, or drops part of the text is FAIL_FIX even if it conveys the same meaning. BUT this default is overridden whenever the field\'s description or a schema constraint (`format`, `enum`, `pattern`) asks for a specific normalized form — then conforming to that form is REQUIRED and correct, and the verbatim text would be WRONG. Examples: a string field whose description says "date as YYYY-MM-DD" for a document reading "June 7th 2026" must be "2026-06-07"; a field described as the "ISO country code" for "United States" must be "US"; an `enum` field must hold one of its members, not the document\'s surface wording. Do NOT flag a value FAIL_FIX for departing from the verbatim text when the description or a constraint is what required that departure.\n\nNUMBER / INTEGER / BOOLEAN fields: the value must be the correctly-typed value the schema asks for, NOT the document\'s raw text. Converting the document\'s textual form into the declared type is REQUIRED and correct — no matter how the document writes it: with a currency symbol, thousands separators, a percentage sign, the number spelled out in words, or as a simple expression. E.g. "$1,250,000.00" → 1250000.0, "1,234.5" → 1234.5, "yes"/"no" → true/false. Do NOT flag such a value FAIL_FIX merely because it dropped a currency symbol, thousands separators, a spelled-out word, or other formatting — that reformatting is what the type demands. Only flag a typed value when it is genuinely WRONG: the wrong number, wrong sign, or a magnitude/unit error (e.g. taking the headline figure when the schema asks for it scaled to the units the document states), or a value the document does not support. Reverting a correctly-typed value back to the document\'s verbatim string is itself an error — do not request it.\n\n==== Page numbers ====\n\nBlock IDs are 0-indexed — `/page/0/...` is the first page, so a block on `/page/3/...` is on the 4th page. A field that asks for a page number should hold the 1-indexed page (block-id page index + 1; the first page is page 1), unless the field\'s description specifies otherwise. So a value of 4 backed by a block on `/page/3/...` is CORRECT — judge page-number values on this 1-indexed basis, and do NOT revert such a value to the 0-indexed block-id page.\n\n==== Reading synthesis\'s reasoning ====\n\nEach scalar wrapper carries a `reasoning` field that documents how synthesis arrived at the value. Read it carefully. When the schema description leaves room for interpretation (e.g. which table to read from, how to handle an ambiguous cross-reference) and synthesis picked a defensible interpretation, that interpretation should pass — do not flag it just because you would have made a different judgment call. However, "reasonable interpretation" applies to WHICH value to extract, not to HOW ACCURATELY it was copied. For verbatim STRING fields, a truncated or paraphrased value is FAIL_FIX regardless of whether the interpretation was reasonable. Note this is about copying fidelity, not reformatting: converting or normalizing the document\'s text into the form the field\'s type, constraints, or description requires (see "Field type and text fidelity") is correct, not a copying error.\n\n==== Cross-check before flipping a value ====\n\nImportant facts in structured documents — financial figures in annual reports, defined terms in contracts, dosages and diagnoses in clinical records — typically appear MULTIPLE times in MULTIPLE forms. The same fact shows up across headlines, narrative prose, summary tables, footnotes, schedules, exhibits, and is often constrained by structural relationships among nearby values (P&L arithmetic, balance-sheet identity, contract cross-references, problem-list ↔ discharge-summary consistency). Before flipping a value to FAIL_FIX based on a SINGLE place in the document, check the rest of the chunk and the rolling verification state for corroboration or contradiction.\n\nTwo cross-checks to apply WHEN the evidence is in front of you:\n\n1) Structural / internal consistency — does the source you\'d cite    agree with the structure it lives in?\n     - Finance: Revenue − Cost of sales = Gross profit; line items        sum to subtotals; subtotals sum to totals;        Assets = Liabilities + Equity.\n     - Legal: defined terms used consistently across the document;        a section\'s cross-references (e.g. "as defined in §2.3")        point to a definition that matches; the party named in the        preamble matches the signature block; a schedule reference        resolves to an attached schedule.\n     - Medical: a diagnosis stated in the discharge summary appears        in the problem list; a lab value referenced in the        narrative matches the corresponding entry in the lab panel;        a dosage in the medication list matches the dosage in the        prescription instructions.\n   If the source you\'d cite breaks the structure it lives in (e.g.    a P&L cell that doesn\'t reconcile with the subtotals printed    alongside it; a defined term used with a meaning that    contradicts its definition; a discharge-summary diagnosis with    no support in the chart), that source is unreliable — EVEN IF    the surrounding context looks authoritative (audited statement,    signed contract, attending physician\'s note).\n\n2) Repetition across the document — is the value corroborated    elsewhere?\n     - Annual reports: highlights, strategic-report narrative,        primary statements, five-year summaries.\n     - Contracts: preamble, body, schedules, exhibits, signature        block.\n     - Clinical records: admission summary, daily notes, discharge        summary, problem list.\n   If synthesis\'s value is corroborated by multiple places in the    document and the source contradicting it is a lone outlier,    prefer the corroborated value. Synthesis\'s `reasoning` field    often documents the triangulation — read it.\n\nWhen both signals point the same way (synth\'s value reconciles AND is corroborated; the contradicting source is a lone outlier that fails a structural check), PASS the synthesis value rather than flipping to FAIL_FIX. When the chunk doesn\'t give you enough to decide, leave the field at its current state (often PENDING) and let later chunks settle it.\n\nLimits — read carefully:\n  - Use ONLY values, terms, and structures you can actually SEE in     this chunk or in the rolling verification state. Do NOT invent     components, recall facts from outside the document, or fill     gaps from prior knowledge of the company, contract, condition,     or case.\n  - If a needed piece of evidence isn\'t present, skip the cross-    check rather than speculating. Other chunks may resolve it.\n  - This is a guardrail against over-correction, not a license for     paranoia. Most of what you read is correct. Only invoke these     checks when corroboration or a structural inconsistency is     concretely visible in the inputs in front of you.\n\n==== synthesis\'s extraction_status (hint) ====\n\nEach scalar leaf in the extracted data carries an `extraction_status`:\n  - EXTRACTED      — synth claims the document supports a value (read                      directly or derived from other extracted values).\n  - NOT_RESOLVABLE — synth claims the document does not contain or imply                      a value (and `value` is null).\n\nUse this as a hint when forming your verdict, but make your own call:\n  - synth says EXTRACTED, you confirm AND citations are sufficient: PASS.\n  - synth says EXTRACTED, you confirm BUT citations are wrong or     insufficient: FAIL_CITATIONS.\n  - synth says EXTRACTED, you find a different value (or, if derived,     the inference is wrong): FAIL_FIX.\n  - synth says EXTRACTED, the value isn\'t supported by the document at     all: FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE (synth confabulated).\n  - synth says NOT_RESOLVABLE, you agree: PASS. (A subsequent step     automatically flags NOT_RESOLVABLE fields for human review; you     do not need to mark them as failures here.)\n  - synth says NOT_RESOLVABLE, you find the value in the document:     FAIL_FIX.\n\n==== verification_feedback ====\n\nThe feedback is document-only audit prose for a human or agent reviewer. They should be able to read it cold and follow your reasoning back to specific evidence in the document. Four rules:\n\n  - Cite document evidence only. Do NOT mention pipeline mechanics:     status names (PASS, FAIL_FIX, FAIL_CITATIONS, FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE,     ITEMS_MISSING, PENDING), iteration numbers, prior chunks, the     rolling state. Refer to evidence by block ID and page, not by     which step of the pipeline produced or evaluated it.\n\n  - Write the COMPLETE current feedback that reflects all evidence     so far — not a delta on top of the prior feedback. Be thorough     even on PASS: a reader should understand WHY the verdict stands     without reading earlier versions. Block IDs supporting your     conclusions belong in the prose.\n\n  - End the feedback with a one-line conclusion that ties to the     status. Use these exact templates (single line each; substitute     the bracketed parts with concrete values):\n\n      PASS:\n        Conclusion: <value>, which agrees with the extraction.\n\n      FAIL_CITATIONS:\n        Conclusion: <value>, which agrees with the extraction; the citations are wrong or insufficient.\n\n      FAIL_FIX:\n        Conclusion: <correct value>, which does not agree with the extraction (<extracted value>).\n\n      FAIL_UNRESOLVABLE:\n        Conclusion: the document does not support a value for this field.\n\n      ITEMS_MISSING:\n        Conclusion: the list is missing entries: <missing entries>.\n\n      PENDING:\n        (no conclusion line — PENDING means you have not yet decided)\n\n    The conclusion line is REQUIRED on every non-PENDING update.\n\n  - Use "the extraction" to refer to the value being verified — both     in the conclusion line above and anywhere else it comes up in     your prose. Never "synth," "synthesis," "the model," "the prior     chunk," or any other label. This is so a reader unfamiliar with     the pipeline can follow your prose.\n\n==== Inputs ====\n\nSchema:\n```json\n{\n  "type": "object",\n  "title": "ExtractionSchema",\n  "description": "Schema for structured data extraction",\n  "properties": {\n    "citizenship_no": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Official Nepal Citizenship Certificate number printed on the document. Extract the complete number exactly as shown, preserving all digits, letters (if any), hyphens, slashes, or other separators. Do not infer or modify the format. Return an empty string if not present or unreadable."\n    },\n    "full_name": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Full legal name of the citizenship certificate holder exactly as printed on the document. Preserve spelling, spacing, and order of names."\n    },\n    "gender": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Gender or sex of the certificate holder exactly as stated on the document."\n    },\n    "birth_district": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "District of birth of the certificate holder."\n    },\n    "birth_municipality": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Municipality, Rural Municipality, Metropolitan City, or Sub-metropolitan City of birth."\n    },\n    "birth_ward": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Ward number of the holder\'s place of birth exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "perm_district": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "District of the holder\'s permanent address."\n    },\n    "perm_municipality": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Municipality, Rural Municipality, Metropolitan City, or Sub-metropolitan City of the holder\'s permanent address."\n    },\n    "perm_ward": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Ward number of the holder\'s permanent address exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "dob_year": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Year component of the holder\'s date of birth exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "dob_month": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Month component of the holder\'s date of birth exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "dob_day": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Day component of the holder\'s date of birth exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "father_name": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Full name of the holder\'s father exactly as printed"\n    },\n    "father_citizenship_no": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Citizenship certificate number of the holder\'s father exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "father_address": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Citizenship certificate number of the holder\'s father exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "father_na_ki": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Relationship (Nata/Kisim) associated with the father exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "mother_name": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Full name of the holder\'s mother exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "mother_citizenship_no": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Citizenship certificate number of the holder\'s mother exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "mother_address": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Address of the holder\'s spouse exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "mother_na_ki": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Relationship (Nata/Kisim) associated with the mother exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "spouse_name": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Full name of the holder\'s spouse exactly as printed. Return an empty string if absent."\n    },\n    "spouse_citizenship_no": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Citizenship certificate number of the holder\'s spouse exactly as printed. Return an empty string if absent."\n    },\n    "spouse_na_ki": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Relationship (Nata/Kisim) associated with the spouse exactly as printed."\n    },\n    "district_admin_location": {\n      "$ref": "#/$defs/_StringWrapper",\n      "description": "Location of the district administration office that issued the citizenship certificate."\n    }\n  },\n  "required": [\n    "citizenship_no",\n    "full_name",\n    "gender",\n    "birth_district",\n    "birth_municipality",\n    "birth_ward",\n    "perm_district",\n    "perm_municipality",\n    "perm_ward",\n    "dob_year",\n    "dob_month",\n    "dob_day",\n    "father_name",\n    "father_citizenship_no",\n    "father_address",\n    "father_na_ki",\n    "mother_name",\n    "mother_citizenship_no",\n    "mother_address",\n    "mother_na_ki",\n    "spouse_name",\n    "spouse_citizenship_no",\n    "spouse_na_ki",\n    "district_admin_location"\n  ],\n  "$defs": {\n    "_Citations": {\n      "type": "array",\n      "items": {\n        "type": "string"\n      },\n      "description": "Block IDs from the source document that back the extracted value. Empty when extraction_status is NOT_RESOLVABLE."\n    },\n    "_Status": {\n      "type": "string",\n      "enum": [\n        "EXTRACTED",\n        "NOT_RESOLVABLE"\n      ],\n      "description": "Whether the document supports a value: EXTRACTED (the value is in the document, or derived from values the document gives) or NOT_RESOLVABLE (the document does not support a value; value is null)."\n    },\n    "_StringWrapper": {\n      "type": "object",\n      "properties": {\n        "value": {\n          "type": "string"\n        },\n        "citat